The most interesting part to me was the entity resolution pipeline (deterministic matching + probabilistic linkage with Splink + LLM-verified golden records) used to reconcile the same organization appearing under dozens of name variants across datasets.

The deterministic approach seems useful for quickly resolving exact matches, but it becomes limited with real-world data because of:

* typos,
* naming variations,
* acronyms,
* and inconsistent formatting.

That is where the probabilistic approach with Splink becomes interesting.
Instead of relying only on strict matching rules, the system calculates match probabilities, which allows for more flexible and nuanced matching while reducing some false positives and false negatives.

The LLM layer then seems to act as an additional semantic/contextual validation step for the most ambiguous cases that are harder to resolve using purely statistical approaches.

I think the main strength of the pipeline is the combination of the three approaches together, since each one helps compensate for some of the limitations of the others.

One possible improvement could be adding a lightweight human QA/audit sampling step at the end of the pipeline to randomly review a subset of LLM decisions in order to monitor quality and detect potential linkage errors or incorrect merges.

A similar approach could potentially be useful in our own databases for fraud detection or analytics use cases.

Another interesting aspect is the explainability of the system.

The project seems to rely on scoring models rather than a simple fraud/non-fraud binary classification. This likely helps reduce some biases and makes the results easier to explain, audit, and review manually since the scores are based on explicit and interpretable signals.

This also seems useful for risk prioritization and for providing more tangible evidence when reviewing flagged cases.

However, the system is probably not fully explainable end-to-end because the final LLM layer remains relatively opaque compared to the probabilistic and statistical parts of the pipeline, and realistically not all decisions could be manually verified at scale.
